abstract: Although the attendance on Saturday was not quite equal to the two preceding days, there were perhaps as many strangers present as on any previous occasion. Visitors are beginning to flock hitherwards from all parts of the Union. Already the hotels are experiencing a satisfactory increase of business. At the Crystal Palace the number of happy faces who are intent of seeing and being pleased with everything is daily on the increase.

abstract: The Hartford Times speaking of the proposed Monument to General DAVID WOOSTER, says: " The Legislature of this State at its last session voted the sum of 1,500 towards the erection of a monument to the memory of General DAVID WOOSTER, who was killed in battle with the British, at Ridgefield, in 1777. abstract: The city is crowded in every part. The numbers of people daily arriving from abroad are extraordinary. The Hotels are full, and private houses are beginning to be invaded. abstract: The ship Mary Crocker, of Portland, bound from New-York to St. Stephens, N. abstract: The Philadelphia Bulletin discusses, with phrase of edifying gravity, certain of our remarks upon the odds of a war with Austria. abstract: A severe storm swept over Bucks County, Penn., on Monday night, the 25th ult., flooding Tohickon, Pine Run, North Branch, and Tinicum creeks higher than they were known before for manny years, and doing a large amount of damage. abstract: A SLAVE OF GEN. WASHINGTON'S.--It is not generally known to our readers that there is yet living near Cookstown, a slave of Gen. WASHINGTON'S. abstract: MONS. MAILLEFERT'S SUBMARINE-BLASTING OPERATIONS.-This gentleman, it appears, is still busied in demolishing submarine obstructions to navigation. abstract: COFFEE.-There are about a dozen species of the genus to which coffee belongs, but all of them are inhabitants of tropical countries. The Coffea Arabica alone is cultivated, and yields the article known in commerce. Its favorite locality is on hill-sides, at an elevation of from 1,000 to 3,000 feet above the level of the sea.

abstract: Another horrible accident took place on the New-Haven Railroad Tuesday night, by which the engineer was killed, and a fireman badly injured, and the locomotive, tender, and baggage-car smashed to pieces. abstract: ATTEMPT TO ROB A BRIG AND MURDER THE CAPTAIN.--ONE OF THE RIVER THIEVES SHOT DEAD, AND ANOTHER WOUNDED.--About daybreak, on-Sunday morning, the cabin of the brig Alfred Hammond, Capt. THAYER, lying at the foot of Delancy-street, was entered by four thieves, who seized the captain while asleep, chocked him, and attempted to force him through the cabin windows. He, however, awaking, and extricating himself from their grasp, gave the alarm.

abstract: CASTLE GARDEN.--It certainly must be a difficult thing to consult the public taste. abstract: The Pittsburg Despatch, of August 18th, stopped the press to announce the commission of a horrible murder in Allegheny city. abstract: The eastern part of Alabama resembles the western part of Georgia, which I have described. abstract: A PERTINENT INQUIRY.--When is Prince-street to be completer, and continued through to Concold? This is a question which has been anxiuosly mooted in certain quarters. abstract: The Picture Gallery is in process of completion, under the superintendence of Signor PIATTI. abstract: A public meeting was held this afternoon, to consider the recent collision on the Worcester Railroad. abstract: OVERBOARD.--A man residing in Union-avenue, employed in a store in New-street, New-York. while returning home by the Peck-slip ferry, at a late hour on Saturday night, walked off of the boat into the slip, on the Williamsburg side, in consequence of the darkness of the bridge and slip. abstract: The harbor of Quebec is doubtless one the finest on the continent. abstract: Have you enough to do, good friend! Then do it, and be thankful that you have. We stand at the opening of an avenue through which people pour their wants upon the world, and we know something of what "wants" are. Some want money. And such can certainly get it, by paying for it. Some want land; that, money will always buy.

abstract: The arrival of the Georgia put us in possession of our usual files from Australia. The papers are dated down to the 16th of May. The general news is not of much importance. The commercial intelligence is worthy of attention. By a return from the convict department, it appears that 1,721 convicts arrived in the colony of North South Wales, from the 30th of June, 1852, to the 31st of January, 1853.
